<p><b>Matthew Simmons</b>, chairman and <a href="/wiki/Chief_executive_officer" title="Chief executive officer">CEO</a> of <a href="/wiki/Simmons_%26_Company_International" title="Simmons &amp; Company International">Simmons &amp; Company International</a>, is a prominent oil-industry insider and one of the world's leading experts on the topic of <a href="/wiki/Peak_oil" title="Peak oil">peak oil</a>. Simmons was motivated by the <a href="/wiki/1973_energy_crisis" title="1973 energy crisis" class="mw-redirect">1973 energy crisis</a> to create an investment banking firm catering to oil companies. In his previous capacity, he served as energy adviser to U.S. President <a href="/wiki/George_W._Bush" title="George W. Bush">George W. Bush</a>.</p>
<p>Matthew Simmons believes the <a href="/wiki/Club_of_Rome" title="Club of Rome">Club of Rome</a> predictions were correct. Simmons is an advisor to the <a href="/wiki/Oil_Depletion_Analysis_Centre" title="Oil Depletion Analysis Centre" class="mw-redirect">Oil Depletion Analysis Centre</a>. He is a member of the <a href="/wiki/National_Petroleum_Council" title="National Petroleum Council">National Petroleum Council</a> and the <a href="/wiki/Council_on_Foreign_Relations" title="Council on Foreign Relations">Council on Foreign Relations</a>. He believes a careful assessment of Saudi Arabian oil reserves is the most significant issue shaping <a href="/wiki/Petroleum_politics" title="Petroleum politics">petroleum politics</a>.</p>
<p>Simmons is the author of the book <i>Twilight in the Desert: The Coming Saudi Oil Shock and the World Economy</i>. His examination of oil reserve decline rates helped raise awareness of the unreliability of Middle East oil reserves as the published reports have never been <a href="/wiki/Verification" title="Verification">verified</a>.</p>
